arg(pro74).  % [pro] They report the increase would shave $ 7.6 billion off annual government spending on income-support programs .
arg(pro5).  % [pro] The gap between the rich and the poor was the widest since the 1920s.
arg(pro55).  % [pro] After 90 consecutive days of employment or the employee reaches 20 years of age, whichever comes first, the employee must receive the current federal minimum wage or the state minimum wage, whichever is higher.
arg(pro62).  % [pro] Giving workers more money is small potatoes compared with what corporations and the rich are receiving all the time.
arg(pro2).  % [pro] Raising the minimum wage would increase school attendance.
arg(pro2b).  % [pro] Raising the minimum wage would decrease high school drop-out rates.
arg(pro27).  % [pro] Taxpayers pay about $243 billion each year in indirect subsidies to the fast‑food industry because the fast‑food industry pays wages so low that taxpayers must fund public benefits for the fast‑food workers.
arg(con105).  % [con] According to James Sherk , MA , Senior Policy Analyst at the Heritage Foundation , a single mother working full time and earning the federal minimum wage of $ 7.25 an hour would be over $ 260 a month worse off if the minimum wage were raised to $ 10.10 : " While her market income rises by $ 494 , she loses $ 71 in EITC [ earned income tax credit ] refunds , pays $ 37 more in payroll taxes and $ 45 more in state income taxes .
arg(con63).  % [con] If low-income workers earned more money, their dependence on government benefits would decrease.
arg(con63b).  % [con] If low-income workers earned more money, their eligibility for government benefits would decrease.
arg(con106).  % [con] If an employer has a tight compensation budget and the minimum wage is raised, the employer can no longer compensate the same number of employees at the higher wage.
arg(con106b).  % [con] If an employer has a tight compensation budget and the minimum wage is raised, the employer must make layoffs to remain within budget.
arg(con36).  % [con] Employers in low‑cost areas such as Mississippi would need to spend a larger proportion of their revenue to pay minimum‑wage employees than employers in higher‑cost areas such as Hawaii.
arg(con36b).  % [con] Employers in low‑cost areas would be unable to cover the higher labor cost by raising prices because customers in those areas could not afford higher prices.
arg(con84).  % [con] Raising the federal tipped minimum wage ($2.13 per hour since 1991) would not lead to restaurant job losses.
arg(con104).  % [con] A minimum wage job is suppose to be an entry level stepping stone – not a career goal .
arg(con21).  % [con] Seventy percent of US chief financial officers said they would increase contracting, outsourcing, or move production outside the United States if the minimum wage were raised to $10 an hour.

